// Regression floor for known_bugs_2.md #96 [P0] (LLVM native backend heap
// corruption that surfaces at a LATER, unrelated heap-touching call — the
// crash-later P0.3 shape). Distilled from Atlantis Track 08's Auth::testPbkdf2
// `VerifyResult r = await verifyPassword(...)` sequence, the live manifestation
// of #96's original CPR-segfault symptom.
//
// The ingredient: `await` a Promise whose resolved value is a VALUE STRUCT with
// a reference-typed field (`string? note` here forces the boxed representation,
// bug #66). Op::Await reads the promise's `value` field BORROWED (lvrt_await's
// getfield, runtime/lv_runtime.c), and the dk==1 wrap's retain NO-OPS on a value
// class — so the await result register holds a bare borrowed alias of the
// promise's stored struct, never gaining a real count. The consuming CopyVal
// makes an independent copy into the local, but the borrowed alias survives to
// frame exit; once the awaited Promise (and the struct it owns) is freed in the
// same frame, releaseAllRegs (src/LlvmGen.cpp) releases the stale alias — reads
// the freed block's classId (garbage), the value-class skip in lv_is_counted
// fails, and the "release" decrements a freed block's freelist next-pointer
// word. Heap corruption surfacing far from the site: the `churn()` loop below
// re-allocates the SAME size class (small boxed value structs), pulls the
// corrupted freelist node, and SIGSEGVs inside lv_alloc_heap on LLVM before the
// fix; in Track 08's real corpus the same corruption (planted in testPbkdf2)
// core-dumps ~eight test-functions later, partway through the session strategy.
// Same borrowed-value-struct-alias family as #95 (method-receiver window) and
// #99 (loop-var early return).
//
// Fixed in src/Lower.cpp: a value-struct `await` result register is recorded
// (borrowedAwaitStructs_) and voided at every frame-exit path before control
// reaches releaseAllRegs, exactly as #99 does for a for-in loop var. Clean on
// run/ir/cpp/llvm; pinned here so a future lowering change can't silently
// regress it (verified red->green: SIGSEGV on LLVM before, correct output after).
struct Vr {
    bool ok;
    string? note;          // reference-typed field -> boxed value struct (#66)
    new Vr(bool ok, string? note) { this.ok = ok; this.note = note; }
}

Promise<Vr> verify(bool good) {
    Promise<Vr> p = Promise();
    p.resolve(good ? Vr(true, "up") : Vr(false, None));
    return p;
}

// Several `await`-into-a-value-struct-local sites, then an explicit Promise
// return — the exact shape of testPbkdf2. Each await leaves a borrowed alias
// that must be voided before this frame's releaseAllRegs.
Promise<int> runChecks() {
    int okCount = 0;
    Vr r1 = await verify(true);
    if (r1.ok) { okCount = okCount + 1; }
    Vr r2 = await verify(false);
    if (r2.ok) { okCount = okCount + 1; }
    Vr r3 = await verify(true);
    if (r3.ok) { okCount = okCount + 1; }
    Vr r4 = await verify(true);
    if (r4.ok) { okCount = okCount + 1; }
    Vr r5 = await verify(false);
    if (r5.ok) { okCount = okCount + 1; }
    Promise<int> done = Promise();
    done.resolve(okCount);
    return done;
}

// Later heap-touching work over the SAME size class the freed value structs
// used; pulls the corrupted freelist node — the corruption planted above
// surfaces here (SIGSEGV in lv_alloc_heap on LLVM before the fix).
int churn(int n) {
    int acc = 0;
    for (int i in 1..n) {
        Array<Vr> a = [Vr(i % 2 == 0, "n")];
        Vr got = a.at(0);
        if (got.ok) { acc = acc + 1; }
    }
    return acc;
}

int oks = await runChecks();
console.writeln("oks=" + oks.toString());
console.writeln("about to churn");
int c = churn(500);
console.writeln("churn acc=" + c.toString());
